{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"498221d1-4e6e-4d00-a828-11bafc392288","content":"The repository is empty, so this is a general knowledge question. Here's the process:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — macOS disables them by default:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Check for Apple crash reports** — macOS automatically writes `.ips` / `.crash` files to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These contain stack traces, register state, and loaded images.\n\n3. **Generate a core dump via `lldb`** — if you can reproduce the crash:\n   ```bash\n   lldb -- ./MyApp\n   run\n   # after crash:\n   process save-core /tmp/myapp.core\n   ```\n\n4. **Use `/cores/` directory** — if core dumps are enabled (`ulimit -c unlimited`), macOS writes them to `/cores/core.<pid>`. You may also need:\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/cores/core.%P\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./MyApp -c /cores/core.12345\n   bt all          # backtraces for all threads\n   register read   # register state\n   ```\n\n**Key note:** NativeAOT binaries include native debug symbols, so `lldb` can resolve frames directly — no need for managed debuggers like `dotnet-dump`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a92536fe-bd50-4f89-aefc-d12fc4079dc4","outputTokens":366,"requestId":"2C47:1986A2:1460468:1729555:69F94D8C"},"id":"e1423cf0-8e00-4170-8760-38d7da114378","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:53:29.739Z","parentId":"a4f42805-7f14-4291-aa67-2faf7eaf3792"}
